Klarna Case Study - Machine Learning¶

Author: Paul Egorov

Date: 2021-11-07

Email: spry.amp.0w@icloud.com

Case Description¶

This case consists of a supervised learning example, similar to what some Klarna teams are working with on a daily basis.

Your task is to predict the probability of default for the data points in the attached ␀le where that variable is missing. Your solution should contain your predictions in a .csv ␀le with two columns, uuid and pd (probability of default==1). Once done, you should expose this model with an API endpoint on a cloud provider of your choice. We (mostly) use Python for modeling at Klarna so please use this programming language to craft your submission. There’s a bonus point if you use AWS in your deployment.

When you’re ready, send us your solution. Include the code, details on how to query the endpoint, and a 1-pager that summarizes how you built and validated your model.

Our advice is to avoid spending too much time optimizing your prediction results. We want to evaluate how you structure, reason and evaluate the problem. Showing off your skills in model building, analysis, and software engineering is more important than maximizing predictive performance. Similarly, further information about the variables below is not available, as your domain knowledge and skills in business translation will be assessed at a later stage. Good luck!!

3.2 Special utils function for model evalation¶

I have created special utility function, which you can find in utils.py. It helped me to evaluate set of model and easily conduct preprocessing experiments. You just set up a list of models (estimators), set up preprocessing pipeline and run utils.evalute_models_cv.

Example:

entries_bl, results_bl = utils.evalute_models_cv(estimators, 
                  estimators_names, 
                  preprocessor, 
                  'prep v1', 
                  *train_test_split(
                        df_bl.drop(['uuid','default'], axis = 1), 
                        df_bl['default'], 
                        test_size=0.2,
                        random_state=0)
                 )

Output features:

  • Name
  • f1
  • f1_test
  • roc_auc_test
  • StdDev(%)
  • Time(s)
  • fpr
  • tpr

3.4 Modeling experiment v2¶

Preprocessing setup¶

  1. Delete rows with null target variables ('default')
  2. Convert boolean feature to int
  3. Impute numeric columns, which contains null data (median strategy)
  4. Impute categorical columns, which contains null data (most_frequent strategy)
  5. Apply dummies encoding for nominal_categorical_cols
  6. Apply scaling for numerical columns
In [37]:
df_bl2 = df[df['default'].isna() == False] #1

#3,6
numeric_transformer_imp = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('scaler', RobustScaler())])
#4,5
categorical_transformer_imp = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('onehot', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))])

preprocessor2 = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numeric_transformer_imp, numeric_cols  + categorical_num_cols ),

        top_num_corr_features = list(cols_corr_df.index.values[1:num_top_features+1])

        numeric_transformer_imp = Pipeline(steps=[
            ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),

        #4,5
        categorical_transformer_imp = Pipeline(steps=[
            ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),

        top_numeric_transformer_imp_poly = Pipeline(steps=[

    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('onehot', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))])

    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('scaler', RobustScaler()),
    ('poly', PolynomialFeatures(degree = poly_degree))
])

Conclusion¶

After conducting ~40 experimtents with 5 models and different preprocessing techniques, the best results on test set shows LGBM Classifier with next preprocessing steps:

  1. Delete rows with null target variables ('default')
  2. Convert boolean feature to int
  3. Impute numeric_cols + categorical_num_cols, which contains null data (median strategy) + RobustScaler
  4. Feature engineering 1: Create 10 age bins
  5. Impute categorical_text_cols with SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent') and apply OHE for categorical_text_cols + age_bins
  6. Feature engineering 2: select top5 numeric cols by correlation coeff with target + age column and apply Imputer, Scaler and PolyFeatures (degree = 2)
  7. Apply SmoteKNN for data balancing

4. Business interpretation¶

We have chosen best model based on f1-score for positive class (default = 1), it is just general purpose - let's try to do out best and build a model, which can be good at both concerns (precision and recall). Recall for positive class with default threshold equals to 0.19, whick means, that 19% of clients with flag "is risk of default" would be classified correctly.

But this interpretation can be different for different business tasks.

For example, if we will use this model for onboarding new clients, we should understand, that the profit on good customer loan is not equal to the loss on one bad customer loan. So, in this case, we should set up the threshold for our model so that recall is high.

For example, we can do something like this (threshold = 0.1):

In [88]:
utils.fit_predict_after_split(
    LGBMClassifier(), 
    X_train_prep_smt, #after smote + prepv2
    X_test_prep, #after prepv2
    y_train_smt, #after smote
    y_test,
    threshold = 0.1
)

F1-score: 0.16
AUC: 0.90

Classification report:
              precision    recall  f1-score   support

 Default = 0       1.00      0.90      0.94     17733
 Default = 1       0.09      0.71      0.16       263

    accuracy                           0.89     17996
   macro avg       0.54      0.80      0.55     17996
weighted avg       0.98      0.89      0.93     17996

Now we see that Recall = 0.7 - 70% of clients with flag "in risk of default" classified correctly. But we have some consequences: 10% of our "good" clients may be mistakenly categorized as "default". Is it better for business? Will there be a positive economic effect from such a threshold? ...

So we should clearly identify the business goal of our model, talk to stakeholders and only after that we can choose appropriate evaluation strategy/appropriate metric.
